1S Pass 1NT Pass 2C Pass 2NT Pass 3NT Pass Pass Pass
{South opens 1\S. What should you bid? 
You have 11 points, enough to respond 2\C, (or 2\D), in standard bidding, but not when using 2/1. So you bid 1NT, showing 6-12 points.
South rebids 2\c.  Again, this doesn't promise more than 3\c - it's just leaving room for us to describe our hand with our second bid.  What do we bid now? 

We know South doesn't have 4 \Hs, so we show our above-minimum hand by bidding 2NT.
South has extra values and raises to 3NT.
South is happy to play Notrump. He assumes we must have something useful in \Ds and bids 3NT.
3NT seems to be a good contract. There are 8 top tricks and possibilities for a ninth winner in either \Ss, \Ds, or, (the best chance), \Cs.}

